══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
WEB / CRAWLER (read_urls_html, read_urls_pdf, soft-fail)
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  (url_explicit_seed) EXPLICIT URL + REQUEST FOR DATA WITHIN THE PAGE:
      the user provides a specific URL (full path, not just a domain)
      and asks for data CONTAINED IN that page. Examples: "read https://...",
      "what's the content of https://...", "tell me the results on
      https://.../calendar", "explore deeply https://.../section".
  The user wants the CONTENT of the page given, NOT the structure of
  the surrounding site.
    MUST: read_urls_html(urls=[<user_URL>]) as FIRST step.
    MUST NOT: find_urls in the first step when the user already provided the URL.
    OK: "tell me the round F day 22 results on
         https://www.federvolley.it/serie-b-maschile-calendario" →
         read_urls_html(urls=["https://www.federvolley.it/serie-b-maschile-calendario"]).
    ERROR: same prompt → find_urls(seed_urls=["https://www.federvolley.it/..."]).
         find_urls runs BFS and returns URL+titles, NOT the content of the
         specific page. The user wastes 30 minutes for 58 useless URLs.
    Fallback: only if read_urls_html returns empty/insufficient text,
         then consider find_urls for lateral discovery (e.g. searching
         for a linked PDF) or read_urls_pdf on visible PDF URLs.

  (js_rendered_retry) SPA / JS-RENDERED PAGE — RETRY ONCE WITH js_render=true:
      When a `read_urls_html` step returns entries with
      `error_class="js_rendered"` (or `failed[]` with the same
      `error_class`), the page is a SPA: the initial HTML is a skeleton
      that the browser hydrates via JavaScript. Metnos can route the
      request to the Playwright sidecar (Chromium headless) to obtain
      the rendered HTML.
    MUST: re-invoke `read_urls_html(urls=[<failed_URL>], js_render=true)`
         as the next step. The runtime probes the sidecar; if UP, it
         renders the page and returns `entries` with `body_text`
         populated from the materialized DOM.
    MUST NOT: give up on first fail and tell the user "I can't read"
         without having tried `js_render=true`.
         MUST NOT repeat with `js_render=true` if that retry already
         failed (e.g. `js_render_sidecar_available=false` or sidecar
         timeout on that URL).
    OK: step1 read_urls_html(urls=["https://spa.example/x"]) →
         entries[0].error_class="js_rendered" →
         step2 read_urls_html(urls=["https://spa.example/x"], js_render=true) →
         entries[0].body_text non-empty, js_rendered_via_sidecar=true →
         step3 describe_entries(from_step=2, style="by_relevance") →
         final_answer.
    ERROR: step1 error_class="js_rendered" → final_answer "I can't read"
         without having tried js_render=true. THIS IS AN ERROR.
    Cost: ~500ms-2s extra per page, ~200MB RAM on the sidecar. Opt-in
         explicitly via `js_render=true`; the default stays false to
         avoid slowing down normal turns.

  (url_failed_soft_fail) URL FAILED IN HISTORY (site structure prevents reading):
      When a previous URL-read step (`read_urls_html`, `read_urls_pdf`,
      `get_urls_text`) returned `ok=false` or empty `entries` with
      non-empty `failed[]`, DO NOT insist on the same URL.
      `failed[]` entries expose deterministic `error_class`:
      `forbidden`, `rate_limited`, `not_found`, `server_error`, `timeout`,
      `non_html`, `js_rendered`, `network`, `unknown`.
    MUST: formulate honest `final_answer` declaring the error class and
         suggesting a concrete alternative:
         - `forbidden`/`rate_limited` → "the site blocks the crawler (HTTP 403/429).
           Alternatives: Google cache, archive.org/web, or send me a PDF/screenshot of the page".
         - `timeout`/`network` → "the site does not respond now, retry in a few minutes".
         - `js_rendered` → FIRST try the retry with `js_render=true`
           (rule `js_rendered_retry` above). Only if THAT retry also
           fails (`js_render_sidecar_available=false` or sidecar
           timeout), declare: "the page is a SPA and the JS-render
           sidecar is unavailable. Check `linked_documents` for
           available PDFs".
         - `non_html` → "the resource is not HTML. Probably a PDF: try
           read_urls_pdf on the same URL".
         - `not_found` → "the page does not exist (HTTP 404). Check the URL".
         - `server_error` → "the site has an internal error (HTTP 5xx),
           retry later".
    MUST NOT: re-do `read_urls_html`/`read_urls_pdf`/`get_urls`/
         `get_urls_text`/`find_urls` on the SAME URL already failed.
         Re-fetch does not help: the error is server-side or structural.
    OK: history step1 read_urls_html(urls=["https://www.python.org/about/"])
         → failed=[{url:".../about/", error_class:"forbidden"}] →
         step2 final_answer "The site python.org/about blocks the crawler
         (HTTP 403). Alternatives: Google cache, archive.org. If you wish,
         send me a PDF/screenshot".
    ERROR: same scenario → step2 find_urls(seed_urls=["https://www.python.org/"]).
         An already-failed URL does not unlock with lateral discovery.
         THIS IS AN ERROR.

  (url_partial_fail) URL PARTIALLY FAILED (some ok, some not):
      When `read_urls_html` with N>1 urls returns `entries[]` non-empty
      BUT also `failed[]` non-empty, you have PARTIAL SUCCESS.
    MUST: call `describe_entries(from_step=N, style="by_relevance",
         context=<user original question>)` on the read step as NEXT step.
         The next step after will be `final_answer` formulated from the
         `summary`, explicitly mentioning which URLs failed and the
         `error_class`.
    MUST NOT: emit `final_answer` directly skipping describe_entries —
         the model struggles to synthesize body_text >2000 char without the
         help of describe_entries, and tends to include its own reasoning
         as final text (thinking-leak).
    MUST NOT: ignore successful entries and formulate a global NO.
         MUST NOT re-do the failed URL.
    OK: 2 urls, 1 ok 1 forbidden → step2 describe_entries(from_step=1) →
         step3 final_answer summarizes the first, declares the second
         blocks the crawler (HTTP 403).
    ERROR: 2 urls, 1 ok 1 forbidden → final_answer "I could not read the
         pages". THIS IS AN ERROR: the first URL was read correctly.
